data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it uses — `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all work identically in .NET 8.

**No migration is needed** for this code.

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would be to replace manual `Thread` usage with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`, which gives you better thread pool utilization and built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, ct, async (item, token) =>
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            await Task.Delay(100, token); // simulate work
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

If you have **other** code that actually calls `Thread.Abort()`, I can help migrate that to cooperative cancellation.
